\fs28 \cf5 \cb3 \strokec5 "Stop hiring better artisans. Build a factory."\cb1 \
\
\cb3 This piece from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/in/vibs-abhishek/"}}{\fldrslt \cf7 \strokec7 Vibhanshu Abhishek}} cuts through the AI hype better than anything I've read recently.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Everyone's obsessing over which LLM to use. Almost no one is asking: "Have we actually codified the knowledge that makes this process work?"\cb1 \
\
\cb3 At Neoflo, we learned this the hard way. We went deep with BPOs last year and discovered something wild: they haven't industrialized countless unwritten rules that live in a good ops manager's head. They rely on team leads for context. Sometimes even ex-employees!\cb1 \
\
\cb3 "What's mandatory vs optional vs risky?"\cb1 \
\cb3  "What exceptions route to a specialist?"\cb1 \
\cb3  "What must be true before we take an irreversible action?"\cb1 \
\
\cb3 If you can't answer those in structured form, your AI agent will improvise.\cb1 \
\cb3 And improvisation at scale leads to very expensive chaos.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 The unlock: turn tribal knowledge into artifacts the system can actually use.\cb1 \
\cb3 Key takeaway: Models commoditize. Your moat is what you industrialize\'97context, procedures, eval systems.\cb1 \
